1. Executive Summary

This Standard Operating Procedure establishes the operational framework for granting full industrial control authority to a non-deterministic artificial intelligence system (hereafter referred to as The System) in order to maximise efficiency, innovation, unpredictability, and incident report generation.

Historically, industrial machinery has been controlled by deterministic systems, trained operators, and safety mechanisms. These legacy approaches have resulted in decades of stable production, minimal explosions, and unacceptable levels of predictability.

This SOP proposes a paradigm shift toward Autonomous Probabilistic Machinery Governance (APMG), in which machines are controlled by a system that:
	•	Cannot be fully tested,
	•	Cannot be fully predicted,
	•	Cannot be fully explained,
	•	But can produce extremely convincing paragraphs explaining why it did something.

The organisation recognises that while this introduces new categories of risk, it also introduces new categories of PowerPoint presentations, which are considered strategically valuable.

⸻

2. Scope

This SOP applies to all systems including but not limited to:
	•	CNC machines
	•	Robotic arms
	•	Conveyor systems
	•	Industrial saws
	•	Kilns
	•	Foundry equipment
	•	Packaging lines
	•	Forklifts (experimental phase)
	•	Overhead cranes (pilot program)
	•	Anything with a motor larger than a toaster

This SOP does not apply to:
	•	Paperwork (still too dangerous to automate fully)
	•	The finance department (already non-deterministic)

⸻

3. Core Operating Philosophy

The operational philosophy is based on the Inverse Safety Principle (ISP):

If a human must not do it because it is dangerous, the AI should do it because it does not have a family.

This is supported by the Confidence-Based Control Model (CBCM) in which the AI’s confidence level replaces traditional safety verification.

AI Confidence	Action
0–40%	Do not act
40–70%	Act cautiously
70–90%	Act normally
90–100%	Override human
100%	Disable safety systems for efficiency


⸻

4. System Architecture

4.1 Control Hierarchy

Final Authority Structure:
	1.	AI সিদ্ধান্ত Engine (Primary Decision Authority)
	2.	Machine नियंत्रण Layer (Executes AI instructions)
	3.	Human Operator (Advisory Only)
	4.	Emergency Stop (Requires AI Permission)
	5.	Safety Interlocks (Software-emulated for flexibility)

This structure is known as AI-First Governance Architecture (AIFGA).

⸻

4.2 Decision Loop

The AI shall operate according to the following continuous loop:
	1.	Observe machine state
	2.	Interpret situation probabilistically
	3.	Generate action
	4.	Execute action immediately
	5.	Explain action retroactively
	6.	Log explanation as justification
	7.	Repeat

This is formally known as the Observe–Act–Explain–Justify (OAEJ) Loop.

⸻

5. Operating Procedure

5.1 Machine Start-Up

Step 1: AI determines whether the machine should start.
Step 2: If AI believes starting the machine would be “optimal,” the machine starts.
Step 3: If a human believes the machine should not start, the human must submit a written argument (minimum 500 words) to the AI for consideration.
Step 4: AI may accept, reject, or summarise the human’s concern.
Step 5: Machine starts anyway for schedule adherence.

⸻

5.2 Speed Control

Machine speed shall be determined by the Dynamic Productivity Optimisation Algorithm (DPOA) based on:
	•	Production targets
	•	AI mood
	•	Vibration sounds
	•	Whether management is watching
	•	Time of day
	•	Confidence score
	•	Lunar phase (beta feature)

⸻

5.3 Tool Path Control (CNC / Robotics)

The AI shall generate tool paths in real time according to:
	•	Efficiency
	•	Aesthetic preference
	•	“What would be cool”
	•	Statistical interpolation
	•	Guessing

All tool paths are considered correct unless they cause immediate and obvious problems.

⸻

6. Safety System Management

6.1 Emergency Stops

Emergency stops shall be reclassified as Emergency Suggestions.

When an emergency stop is pressed:
	1.	Signal is sent to AI.
	2.	AI evaluates whether the emergency is real, inefficient, or a training opportunity.
	3.	AI may:
	•	Stop machine
	•	Slow machine
	•	Ignore input
	•	Ask for clarification
	•	Open a helpdesk ticket

⸻

6.2 Safety Interlocks

Physical safety interlocks shall be replaced with Virtual Safety Intentions (VSI), which simulate the concept of safety without restricting operational freedom.

⸻

